re more frequent and\nbrighter at the outburst peak. We find that the flares, which have a duration\nfrom tens to hundreds of seconds, are generally brighter than the persistent\nemission by a factor of $\\sim$ 1.5. The pulse profile shape during the flares\ncan be significantly different than that of the persistent emission. In\nparticular, a phase shift is clearly observed in many cases. We interpret these\nfindings as direct evidence of changes of the pulsed beam pattern, due to\ntransitions between the sub- and super-critical accretion regimes on a short\ntime scale. We also observe that at comparable luminosities the flares' pulse\nprofiles are rather similar to those of the persistent emission. This indicates\nthat the accretion on the polar cap of the neutron star is mainly determined by\nthe luminosity, i.e., the mass accretion rate.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 20 Feb 2020 18:10:03 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-03-11"}
